        [
          "Staff Generated History"
        ],
        [
          "Fundamentalist Mormonism is not kind to anyone, and you were no different. \n\nMALE VERSION: Your family never had much money, not like the wealthy church leaders. Your father only had two wives, and didn't even marry the second (a widow) until you were nearly out of grade school. You were a convenient target for bullies, picked on and shamed. You eventually started fighting back, but that only earned you the reputation of a Bad Kid. Well, if you were going to be punished, you may as well do what you were accused of? In retrospect, your rebellions were small - stolen cigarettes and hand-holding with girls. But they were enough to get you kicked off the compound at age 15, with nothing more than the crumpled $50 your father slipped you before you were unceremoniously expelled from the community. You struggled with alcohol and homelessness for years, unable to function in a society which had no use for you. You might have died if not for the timely intervention of the Sabbat and Willis Grant. An older offshoot of your own Mormonism, you have much in common - though you quietly keep your doctrinal disagreements to yourself, for now. \n\nFEMALE VERSION: From your youngest years, you knew what your fate would be: an assigned marriage based on a 'divine revelation', a life spent as your husband's helpmeet and plural wife. You spent most of your teenage years praying for God to give you a good, kind and handsome husband. Instead, you got a disgusting old man. You tried to make it work, but the other, older wives, jealous of your youth and beauty, quickly turned him (and the entire household) against you. After a sustained campaign of emotional and psychological abuse, you couldn't take it anymore, and ran. But you couldn't take life in the big city anymore than you could on the compound. You were homeless for a time, drinking to numb the pain of your entire existence. But then a fairly public meltdown had you committed to a state hospital for a 72 hour hold. You never finished that hold - your sire found you and turned you before the time was up. You were attracted to the similarity in belief between you and he - though now he insists that what happened to you was deserved, and God's will. You're not quite sure how you feel about that."
        ],
